 Synchronous Programming: In this approach, a program follows one instruction after another from top to bottom without skipping or going back until it has executed all instructions. For instance, if we have two scripts A & B running simultaneously then script A cannot be finished before the completion of script B in synchronous programming which may cause performance issues if large tasks are involved and can block other processes that might need CPU resources concurrently as well.

Asynchronous Programming: In contrast to synchronous programming, asynchronous programming allows concurrent execution of operations where an operation does not have to wait for another operation to finish before it starts or continues executing. It's especially useful when dealing with time-consuming tasks like reading large files or making network requests because you can start those while other shorter scripts are still running without blocking the whole program.

Example: Synchronous Programming in JavaScript would look something like this - 

```javascript
function synchronousFetchData(callback) {
    var data = fetchDataFromAPI(); // This function is assumed to be time-consuming, let's say it takes a few seconds
    callback(null, data);
}

var result;
synchronusFetchData(function (err, data) { 
   if (err) throw err;
   else result = "Data retrieved successfully"; // But this line will only execute after the fetch operation is complete.
});
```
In this example above you see that there's a blocking situation where we are waiting for 'fetchDataFromAPI()' to finish before moving on with our function. This can be inefficient and cause performance issues if long-running operations were involved more than once in an application flow. 

Example: Asynchronous Programming in JavaScript would look like this -

```javascript
function asyncFetchData(callback) {
    fetchDataFromAPI((err, data) => { // callback function passed into the async operation
        if (err) throw err;
        else callback(null, data);  // 'callback' from main function is invoked here. Now this function won’t block and can continue its execution right away upon fetching completion signaled by second callback function..
    });
}

asyncFetchData(function(err, data) {
   if (err) throw err; // This line will only execute after the fetch operation is complete
   var result = "Data retrieved successfully";  // And this line too.
});
```
In asynchronous programming we don't block our program logic by waiting for long-running operations to finish before moving on with other tasks or scripts which makes it more efficient and useful in real world applications where concurrent operation is common scenario such as user interactions, network requests etc.

 Here is how you can define such a recursive function called fibonacci(). The logic behind this algorithm lies within its name - 'fibonacci'. It breaks down complex problems into smaller ones and uses solutions to these smaller sub-problems to solve larger problem, which makes it an efficient approach for some types of computation.

```python
def fibonacci(n): 
    if n <= 0: 
        return "Input should be positive integer."
    elif n == 1:
        return 0
    elif n == 2:
        return 1
    else: 
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2) 
```
To execute this function for a particular value of 'n', you can call the above defined function as : 
```python
print(fibonacci(8)) # Output will be 21.
```
